    "summary": "The use of sun-dried mud brick for construction appears among the earliest evidence of permanent architecture in the ancient Near East, with origins traceable to at least the seventh millennium BCE at sites such as Jericho and Çatalhöyük. However, the systematic mass production and standardization of bricks as a primary building material for large urban structures emerged most clearly during the [[event:1617|Uruk period]] in Mesopotamia, approximately 4000–3000 BCE, when temple platforms, warehouses, and city walls were built from millions of identically formed mud bricks.\n\nFired brick, which is far more durable and water-resistant than sun-dried brick, also appears in the archaeological record during the fourth millennium BCE, though it required significant fuel and was therefore used selectively for drainage channels and particularly exposed structures. The standardization of brick sizes — a hallmark of the [[event:1680|Indus Valley Civilization]] as well — indicates the existence of organized construction industries operating under some form of central coordination. Brick construction enabled the physical permanence of cities and allowed architects to design structures of unprecedented scale and complexity.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brick#History",
